{
    "analysis": "Previous step (Executor output) provided global summaries: metric groups (25 datapoints each) show high memory P95 on carts, carts-db, catalogue-db, shipping; very high diskio P95 on carts-db; high CPU P95 on user; elevated socket and workload on carts. trace.csv is empty and error_logs.csv is empty. log.csv shows high log.row_count for front-end, user, queue-master, catalogue, orders, carts and log.error_count is 0 everywhere.\nWhat this means: we have candidates (carts, carts-db, user, catalogue-db, shipping, front-end, queue-master, orders) to inspect. Per rules, the next step is to perform anomaly detection by comparing incident-window metric values against the global thresholds (global P95 computed from the full series). We must filter metric data to the incident window only after computing global P95. The goal is to find which component-KPI time series have consecutive anomalies within the incident window and the earliest anomaly timestamps to guide fault identification.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. 1) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 of value using the full series. 2) Filter metric.csv to the incident window: from '2024-01-20 19:08:51 UTC' to '2024-01-20 19:38:51 UTC' (inclusive). 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) within the incident window calculate: total points in window, number of anomaly points where value >= global_P95, earliest anomaly timestamp (if any), maximum value in-window, and the global_P95. Only return rows where number of anomaly points > 0. Output a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, points_in_window, anomalies_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95. Sort by anomalies_count descending, limit to top 20 rows." }

{
    "analysis": "Executor results show widespread, simultaneous socket-related anomalies starting at 2024-01-20 19:11:00 UTC across infrastructure and middleware (rabbitmq, queue-master, catalogue-db, carts-db, etc.). There are also memory spikes on carts and catalogue-db and a large diskio spike on user. trace.csv is empty and error_logs.csv is empty, so we must rely on metrics and application logs. According to the diagnosis workflow, we now need to narrow candidates to the allowed service-level components (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user) and compare which of these services exhibit sustained anomalies in the incident window and which resource KPIs (socket, cpu, mem, diskio, workload, error) are affected and when their first anomalies occurred. This will let us identify the most likely root-cause service and reason (socket/network vs resource exhaustion).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and log.csv, restrict analysis to the candidate services: ['carts','catalogue','orders','payment','user']. For metric.csv: 1) compute global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using full series. 2) filter to the incident window (2024-01-20 19:08:51 to 2024-01-20 19:38:51 UTC). 3) For each of the five services and each KPI present, report: cmdb_id, kpi_name, points_in_window, anomalies_count (value >= global_P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (if any), max_value_in_window, global_p95. Only include rows where anomalies_count > 0. Sort by anomalies_count descending.\nAlso from log.csv: for the same five services, within the incident window compute for each log_name the points_in_window, max_value_in_window, and earliest timestamp where value >= global P95 (compute global P95 per cmdb_id-log_name using full series). Return compact tables for metrics and logs (limit to top 20 rows each)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous Executor outputs show widespread socket anomalies across infrastructure and middleware beginning at 2024-01-20 19:11:00 UTC, plus sustained, large disk I/O on the user service (25/25 points, earliest 19:11) and memory spikes on carts and catalogue later in the window. Traces and error_logs are empty, so we must rely on metrics and logs. Among the allowed root-cause candidates (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user), the earliest and most sustained anomaly is user.diskio starting at ~19:11, while carts and catalogue show memory/socket spikes later or less persistent, and payment socket anomaly begins later (~19:24). Log.row_count increases corroborate elevated load but log.error_count is zero. According to the workflow, we should now inspect the raw metric values (time series) for the top candidate KPIs to confirm onset times, persistence, and severity before declaring the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, extract detailed in-window data (incident window 2024-01-20 19:08:51 to 2024-01-20 19:38:51 UTC) for these component-KPI pairs: ('user','diskio'), ('carts','mem'), ('carts','socket'), ('catalogue','socket'), ('payment','socket'), ('orders','cpu'), ('orders','mem'). For each pair: (1) compute global P95 using the full series (all timestamps) and include that value; (2) return all rows within the incident window with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, global_p95, is_anomaly (True if value >= global_p95). Sort rows by cmdb_id, kpi_name, timestamp. Limit the total returned rows to 100. Additionally, produce a compact summary table for these pairs with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, points_in_window, anomalies_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (if any), max_value_in_window, global_p95. Return both the detailed rows and the summary table." }

I reviewed the telemetry analysis: metrics show a sustained, high-magnitude disk I/O spike on the user service starting at 2024-01-20 19:11:00 UTC (user.diskio anomalous for the entire incident window), while other services show shorter or later anomalies. Therefore the most likely root cause is the user service experiencing high disk I/O usage.

